{"headline": "A Rich Champagne With Chicken Blintzes", "body": "\nIf you are serving chicken blintzes for a New Year\u2019s Eve supper, why wouldn\u2019t you serve them with Champagne? Particularly a richer Champagne, and especially without the caviar. Regardless of their historic and luxurious association, the saline tang of caviar goes a lot better with vodka.         \n\nSo, why not Champagne? Well, it costs a lot, and good, cheaper alternatives abound. Sparkling Vouvray, for one, especially from a top producer like Hu\u00ebt or Pinon. Or good Cr\u00e9mant de Bourgogne \u2014 sparkling Burgundy, that is. Many American sparkling wines would be delicious with this dish, as would a good cava from Spain. If cost is no obstacle, drink a top Champagne with some age on it. And if, despite the occasion, bubbles repel you, Meursault beckons.\u00a0        ", "url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/25/dining/a-rich-champagne-with-chicken-blintzes.html", "date": "2013-12-23", "description": "Why wouldn\u2019t you serve them with Champagne?"}